notesStmt.note: Yosef ben Yudah ben Merwas: inscribed with his name in the colophon, Toledo, Iyyar 5060 [1300] (folio 184r).
Sulaiman ben Shemu᾿el (?) ben Ḥayim: inscribed with his name as the seller in an Arabic purchase note, 1450 (folio 99v).
Shalom ben Yosef Ḥayim [ .. ] Levi: inscribed with his name in an owner's inscription, 18th century (folio 184r).
Musi 'n Salem al-Gamal: inscribed with his name in an owner's inscription, 18th century (folio 184r).
Judah 'n Musi: inscribed with his name in an unclear purchase note, undated (folio 186v).
Yudah Kamal: inscribed with his name in an owner's inscription, undated (folio 5r).
Manuscript description based on Margoliouth, G.: Catalogue of the Hebrew and Samaritan Manuscripts in the British Museum, London 1965.

msContents.summary: Bible with masorah ('First Ibn Merwas Bible').

layoutDesc.layout: Columns: 3; ruled lines: 32; written lines: 32; Folio 1 is cut off most part. Folios 1 and 4 are later additions. Complete ruling with hard-point. Pricking in outer and inner margins, quire by quire, on recto. Uniform layout, last line of text written ouside ruling. Heading on each leaf. Hebrew foliation from folio 5, starting with 2 until the end of the Pentateuch (folio 99). In the colophon (folio 184), the name of the patron has been erased. The original date 5060 [1300] has been erased and overwritten as 5006 [1246]. The same scribe copied two other bibles in Toledo: Sassoon Collection (MS 508 dated 1307, MS 1208 dated 1334). Numerous decorations: full-page miniature of the Temple implements, 5 full borders of geometric design, masorah in the margins written in microghraphical form, 6 full-page panels of masorah magna in micrographical design, numerous decorated parashah signs. Masorah magna occupies two lines at the top and three lines at the bottom of each page. Joshua, Isaiah, Psalms, and Chronicles begin a new leaf, and Jeremiah begins a new column.

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Sefardi square script of the beginning of 14th century, punctuated.

binding.p: Post-1600. White parchment binding, black tooled. Spine: 'Bible. Hebrew. Brit. Mus. Oriental 2201.'

history.provenance: Acquisition: Purchased by the British Museum in 1879.
